No need for two assert on the value, the first one is redundant, as the second will catch the fail. Also, we shuold be using assertThat with Hamcrest matchers as follows:

assertThat(message.getValue(), is(StringUtils.EMPTY_STRING));

This makes it much clearer as to which is actual and which is expected, which is not at all obvious from 
assertEquals().

Finally, you shold never need to use &quot;new String()&quot;

Dont mix and match assertEquals/assertNull/assertThat. assertThat should be used for all scenarios:

assertThat(actual, nullValue());
assertThat(actual, is(expected));

